e server using a gRPC bidirectional stream. After the initial\n43: // request, the external server is in control over what additional data is sent to it\n44: // and how it should be processed.\n45: //\n46: // By implementing the protocol specified by the stream, the external server can choose:\n47: //\n48: // * Whether it receives the response message at all\n49: // * Whether it receives the message body at all, in separate chunks, or as a single buffer\n50: // * Whether subsequent HTTP requests are transmitted synchronously or whether they are\n51: //   sent asynchronously.\n52: // * To modify request or response trailers if they already exist\n53: //\n54: // The filter supports up to six different processing steps. Each is represented by\n55: // a gRPC stream message that is sent to the external processor. For each message, the\n56: // processor must send a matching response.\n57: //\n58: // * Request headers: Contains the headers from the original HTTP request.\n59: // * Request body: Delivered if they are present and sent in a single message if\n60: //   the BUFFERED or BUFFERED_PARTIAL mode is chosen, in multiple messages if the\n61: //   STREAMED mode is chosen, and not at all otherwise.\n62: // * Request trailers: Delivered if they are present and if the trailer mode is set\n63: //   to SEND.\n64: // * Response headers: Contains the headers from the HTTP response. Keep in mind\n65: //   that if the upstream system sends them before processing the request body that\n66: //   this message may arrive before the complete body.\n67: // * Response body: Sent according to the processing mode like the request body.\n68: // * Response trailers: Delivered according to the processing mode like the\n69: //   request trailers.\n70: //\n71: // By default, the processor sends only the request and response headers messages.\n72: // This may be changed to include any of the six steps by changing the processing_mode\n73: // setting of the filter configuration, or by setting the mode_override of any response\n74: // from the external processor. The latter is only enabled if allow_mode_override is\n75: // set to true. This way, a processor may, for example, use information\n76: // in the request header to determine whether the message body must be examined, or whether\n77: // the proxy should simply stream it straight through.\n78: //\n79: // All of this together allows a server to process the filter traffic in fairly\n80: // sophisticated ways. For example:\n81: //\n82: // * A server may choose to examine all or part of the HTTP message bodies depending\n83: //   on the content of the headers.\n84: // * A server may choose to immediately reject some messages based on their HTTP\n85: //   headers (or other dynamic metadata) and more carefully examine others.\n86: // * A server may asynchronously monitor traffic coming through the filter by inspecting\n87: //   headers, bodies, or both, and then decide to switch to a synchronous processing\n88: //   mode, either permanently or temporarily.\n89: //\n90: // The protocol itself is based on a bidirectional gRPC stream. Envoy will send the\n91: // server\n92: // :ref:`ProcessingRequest \u003cenvoy_v3_api_msg_service.ext_proc.v3.ProcessingRequest\u003e`\n93: // messages, and the server must reply with\n94: // :ref:`ProcessingResponse \u003cenvoy_v3_api_msg_service.ext_proc.v3.ProcessingResponse\u003e`.\n95: //\n96: // Stats about each gRPC call are recorded in a :ref:`dynamic filter state\n97: // \u003carch_overview_advanced_filter_state_sharing\u003e` object in a namespace matching the filter\n98: // name.\n99: //\n100: // [#next-free-field: 18]\n101: message ExternalProcessor {\n102:   reserved 4;\n103: \n104:   reserved \"async_mode\";\n105: \n106:   // Configuration for the gRPC service that the filter will communicate with.\n107:   // The filter supports both the \"Envoy\" and \"Google\" gRPC clients.\n108:   config.core.v3.GrpcService grpc_service = 1 [(validate.rules).message = {required: true}];\n109: \n110:   // By default, if the gRPC stream cannot be established, or if it is closed\n111:   // prematurely with an error, the filter will fail. Specifically, if the\n112:   // response headers have not yet been delivered, then it will return a 500\n113:   // error downstream. If they have been delivered, then instead the HTTP stream to the\n114:   // downstream client will be reset.\n115:   // With this parameter set to true, however, then if the gRPC stream is prematurely closed\n116:   // or could not be opened, processing continues without error.\n117:   bool failure_mode_allow = 2;\n118: \n119:   // Specifies default options for how HTTP headers, trailers, and bodies are\n120:   // sent. See ProcessingMode for details.\n121:   ProcessingMode processing_mode = 3;\n122: \n123:   // Envoy provides a number of :ref:`attributes \u003carch_overview_attributes\u003e`\n124:   // for expressive policies. Each attribute name provided in this field will be\n125:   // matched against that list and populated in the request_headers message.\n126:   // See the :ref:`attribute documentation \u003carch_overview_request_attributes\u003e`\n127:   // for the list of supported attributes and their types.\n128:   repeated string request_attributes = 5;\n129: \n130:   // Envoy provides a number of :ref:`attributes \u003carch_overview_attributes\u003e`\n131:   // for expressive policies. Each attribute name provided in this field will be\n132:   // matched against that list and populated in the response_headers message.\n133:   // See the :ref:`attribute documentation \u003carch_overview_attributes\u003e`\n134:   // for the list of supported attributes and their types.\n135:   repeated string response_attributes = 6;\n136: \n137:   // Specifies the timeout for each individual message sent on the stream and\n138:   // when the filter is running in synchronous mode. Whenever the proxy sends\n139:   // a message on the stream that requires a response, it will reset this timer,\n140:   // and will stop processing and return an error (subject to the processing mode)\n141:   // if the timer expires before a matching response is received. There is no\n142:   // timeout when the filter is running in asynchronous mode. Zero is a valid\n143:   // config which means the timer will be triggered immediately. If not\n144:   // configured, default is 200 milliseconds.\n145:   google.protobuf.Duration message_timeout = 7 [(validate.rules).duration = {\n146:     lte {seconds: 3600}\n147:     gte {}\n148:   }];\n149: \n150:   // Optional additional prefix to use when emitting statistics. This allows to distinguish\n151:   // emitted statistics between configured *ext_proc* filters in an HTTP filter chain.\n152:   string stat_prefix = 8;\n153: \n154:   // Rules that determine what modifications an external processing server may\n155:   // make to message headers. If not set, all headers may be modified except\n156:   // for \"host\", \":authority\", \":scheme\", \":method\", and headers that start\n157:   // with the header prefix set via\n158:   // :ref:`header_prefix \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_config.bootstrap.v3.Bootstrap.header_prefix\u003e`\n159:   // (which is usually \"x-envoy\").\n160:   // Note that changing headers such as \"host\" or \":authority\" may not in itself\n161:   // change Envoy's routing decision, as routes can be cached. To also force the\n162:   // route to be recomputed, set the\n163:   // :ref:`clear_route_cache \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_service.ext_proc.v3.CommonResponse.clear_route_cache\u003e`\n164:   // field to true in the same response.\n165:   config.common.mutation_rules.v3.HeaderMutationRules mutation_rules = 9;\n166: \n167:   // Specify the upper bound of\n168:   // :ref:`override_message_timeout \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_service.ext_proc.v3.ProcessingResponse.override_message_timeout\u003e`\n169:   // If not specified, by default it is 0, which will effectively disable the ``override_message_timeout`` API.\n170:   google.protobuf.Duration max_message_timeout = 10 [(validate.rules).duration = {\n171:     lte {seconds: 3600}\n172:     gte {}\n173:   }];\n174: \n175:   // Prevents clearing the route-cache when the\n176:   // :ref:`clear_route_cache \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_service.ext_proc.v3.CommonResponse.clear_route_cache\u003e`\n177:   // field is set in an external processor response.\n178:   bool disable_clear_route_cache = 11;\n179: \n180:   // Allow headers matching the ``forward_rules`` to be forwarded to the external processing server.\n181:   // If not set, all headers are forwarded to the external processing server.\n182:   HeaderForwardingRules forward_rules = 12;\n183: \n184:   // Additional metadata to be added to the filter state for logging purposes. The metadata\n185:   // will be added to StreamInfo's filter state under the namespace corresponding to the\n186:   // ext_proc filter name.\n187:   google.protobuf.Struct filter_metadata = 13;\n188: \n189:   // If ``allow_mode_override`` is set to true, the filter config :ref:`processing_mode\n190:   // \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_extensions.filters.http.ext_proc.v3.ExternalProcessor.processing_mode\u003e`\n191:   // can be overridden by the response message from the external processing server\n192:   // :ref:`mode_override \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_service.ext_proc.v3.ProcessingResponse.mode_override\u003e`.\n193:   // If not set, ``mode_override`` API in the response message will be ignored.\n194:   bool allow_mode_override = 14;\n195: \n196:   // If set to true, ignore the\n197:   // :ref:`immediate_response \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_service.ext_proc.v3.ProcessingResponse.immediate_response\u003e`\n198:   // message in an external processor response. In such case, no local reply will be sent.\n199:   // Instead, the stream to the external processor will be closed. There will be no\n200:   // more external processing for this stream from now on.\n201:   bool disable_immediate_response = 15;\n202: \n203:   // Options related to the sending and receiving of dynamic metadata.\n204:   MetadataOptions metadata_options = 16;\n205: \n206:   // If true, send each part of the HTTP request or response specified by ProcessingMode\n207:   // without pausing on filter chain iteration. It is \"Send and Go\" mode that can be used\n208:   // by external processor to observe Envoy data and status. In this mode:\n209:   //\n210:   // 1. Only STREAMED body processing mode is supported and any other body processing modes will be\n211:   // ignored. NONE mode(i.e., skip body processing) will still work as expected.\n212:   //\n213:   // 2. External processor should not send back processing response, as any responses will be ignored.\n214:   // This also means that\n215:   // :ref:`message_timeout \u003cenvoy_v3_api_field_extensions.filters.http.ext_proc.v3.ExternalProcessor.message_timeout\u003e`\n216:   // restriction doesn't apply to this mode.\n217:   //\n218:   // 3. External processor may still close the stream to indicate that no more messages are needed.\n219:   //\n220:   // .. warning::\n221:   //\n222:   //    Flow control is necessary mechanism to prevent the fast sender (either downstream client or upstream server)\n223:   //    from overwhelming the external processor when its processing speed is slower.\n224:   //    This protective measure is being explored and developed but has not been ready yet, so please use your own\n225:   //    discretion when enabling this feature.\n226:   //    This work is currently tracked under https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/issues/33319.\n227:   //\n228:   bool observability_mode = 17;\n229: }\n230: \n231: // The MetadataOptions structure defines options for the sending and receiving of\n232: // dynamic metadata. Specifically, which namespaces to send to the server, whether\n233: // metadata returned by the server may be written, and how that metadata may be written.\n234: message MetadataOptions {\n235:   message MetadataNamespaces {\n236:     // Specifies a list of metadata namespaces whose values, if present,\n237:     // will be passed to the ext_proc service as an opaque *protobuf::Struct*.\n238:     repeated string untyped = 1;\n239: \n240:     // Specifies a list of metadata namespaces whose values, if present,\n241:     // will be passed to the ext_proc service as a *protobuf::Any*. This allows\n242:     // envoy and the external processing server to share the protobuf message\n243:     // definition for safe parsing.\n244:     repeated string typed = 2;\n245:   }\n246: \n247:   // Describes which typed or untyped dynamic metadata namespaces to forward to\n248:   // the external processing server.\n249:   MetadataNamespaces forwarding_namespaces = 1;\n250: \n251:   // Describes which typed or untyped dynamic metadata namespaces to accept from\n252:   // the external processing server. Set to empty or leave unset to disallow writing\n253:   // any received dynamic metadata. Receiving of typed metadata is not supported.\n254:   MetadataNamespaces receiving_namespaces = 2;\n255: }\n256: \n257: // The HeaderForwardingRules structure specifies what headers are\n258: // allowed to be forwarded to the external processing server.\n259: //\n260: // This works as below:\n261: //\n262: //   1. If neither ``allowed_headers`` nor ``disallowed_headers`` is set, all headers are forwarded.\n263: //   2. If both ``allowed_headers`` and ``disallowed_headers`` are set, only headers in the\n264: //      ``allowed_headers`` but not in the ``disallowed_headers`` are forwarded.\n265: //   3. If ``allowed_headers`` is set, and ``disallowed_headers`` is not set, only headers in\n266: //      the ``allowed_headers`` are forwarded.\n267: //   4. If ``disallowed_headers`` is set, and ``allowed_headers`` is not set, all headers except\n268: //      headers in the ``disallowed_headers`` are forwarded.\n269: message HeaderForwardingRules {\n270:   // If set, specifically allow any header in this list to be forwarded to the external\n271:   // processing server. This can be overridden by the below ``disallowed_headers``.\n272:   type.matcher.v3.ListStringMatcher allowed_headers = 1;\n273: \n274:   // If set, specifically disallow any header in this list to be forwarded to the external\n275:   // processing server. This overrides the above ``allowed_headers`` if a header matches both.\n276:   type.matcher.v3.ListStringMatcher disallowed_headers = 2;\n277: }\n278: \n279: // Extra settings that may be added to per-route configuration for a\n280: // virtual host or cluster.\n281: message ExtProcPerRoute {\n282:   oneof override {\n283:     option (validate.required) = true;\n284: \n285:     // Disable the filter for this particular vhost or route.\n286:     // If disabled is specified in multiple per-filter-configs, the most specific one will be used.\n287:     bool disabled = 1 [(validate.rules).bool = {const: true}];\n288: \n289:     // Override aspects of the configuration for this route. A set of\n290:     // overrides in a more specific configuration will override a \"disabled\"\n291:     // flag set in a less-specific one.\n292:     ExtProcOverrides overrides = 2;\n293:   }\n294: }\n295: \n296: // Overrides that may be set on a per-route basis\n297: // [#next-free-field: 8]\n298: message ExtProcOverrides {\n299:   // Set a different processing mode for this route than the default.\n300:   ProcessingMode processing_mode = 1;\n301: \n302:   // [#not-implemented-hide:]\n303:   // Set a different asynchronous processing option than the default.\n304:   bool async_mode = 2;\n305: \n306:   // [#not-implemented-hide:]\n307:   // Set different optional attributes than the default setting of the\n308:   // ``request_attributes`` field.\n309:   repeated string request_attributes = 3;\n310: \n311:   // [#not-implemented-hide:]\n312:   // Set different optional properties than the default setting of the\n313:   // ``response_attributes`` field.\n314:   repeated string response_attributes = 4;\n315: \n316:  